<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-08-16T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-08-16T13:00:00-05:00" n="473" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d473">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94111/34: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-16T14:00:00-04:00">August 16, 1937—2
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>152. Please telegraph me as soon as possible your estimate of the
                                probable reaction in China should the President decide to invoke the
                                so-called Neutrality Act of May 1, 1937.<note n="17" xml:id="d473fn17">50 Stat. 121.</note> Any further comments that
                                you may feel moved to offer on the question of the advisability of
                                the President taking such action would be welcomed.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>